    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
            <html:p>And now note, if you focus just on what's not faded out, how similar this looks to the strong Kleene table.
You can use these tables to walk through all nine possibilities, and see that in each case, indeed <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  B]]></fr:tex> has the property.</html:p>
            <html:p>That is, suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = v(B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>; then we are in the top left corner of the strong Kleene table.
Since both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the property, this means that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = u(B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so we are also in the top left corner of the Dunn-Belnap table.
Comparing those two top-left corners, we see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A \lor  B) = u(A \lor  B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>; so in this case <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  B]]></fr:tex> has the property.</html:p>
            <html:p>That preceding paragraph is one of the nine cases that need considering.
Take a moment to walk through at least a few of the other cases at that level of detail, making sure you see how every sinew of the reasoning connects.
If you do it properly, you'll see that it really does work!</html:p>
